  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 32-40.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - Still more to enforce his warning against apostasy, and urge to obedience and faithful adherence to the service of Jehovah, Moses appeals to what they had already experienced of God's grace in the choosing of them to be his people, in his speaking to them to instruct them, and in the miracles which he had wrought for their deliverance and guidance; grace such as had never been showed before to any nation, or heard of since the creation of the world, and by which those who had experienced it were laid under the deepest obligations of gratitude and duty, to love and serve him by whom it had been showed. With this appeal he closes his first address. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 32.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "For",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This connects the statement that fellows with that which precedes as its cause; it is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "because",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Jehovah is a merciful God, that the unparalleled grace showed to Israel had been displayed. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The days that are past",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "e",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". inquire from the earliest time of man's abode on the earth. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "From the one side of heaven unto the other",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; search the records of all times and places, whether any so great a thing has ever happened or been heard of. Deuteronomy 4:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "But in order to accomplish something more than merely preserving the people from apostasy by the threat of punishment, namely, to secure a more faithful attachment and continued obedience to His commands by awakening the feeling of cordial love, Moses reminds them again of the glorious miracles of divine grace performed in connection with the election and deliverance of Israel, such as had never been heard of from the beginning of the world; and with this strong practical proof of the love of the true God, he brings his first address to a close. This closing thought in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:32",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is connected by כּי (for) with the leading idea in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". \"Jehovah thy God is a merciful God,\" to show that the sole ground for the election and redemption of Israel was the compassion of God towards the human race. \"For ask now of the days that are past, from the day that God created man upon the earth, and from one end of the heaven unto the other, whether so great a thing has ever happened, or anything of the kind has been heard of:\" i.e., the history of all times since the creation of man, and of all places under the whole heaven, can relate no such events as those which have happened to Israel, viz., at Sinai (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). From this awfully glorious manifestation of God, Moses goes back in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 4:34",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to the miracles with which God effected the deliverance of Israel out of Egypt. \"Or has a god attempted (made the attempt) to come and take to himself people from people (i.e., to fetch the people of Israel out of the midst of the Egyptian nation), with temptations (the events in Egypt by which Pharaoh's relation to the Lord was put to the test; cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 6:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 7:18-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), with signs and wonders (the Egyptian plagues, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 7:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and with conflict (at the Red Sea: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 14:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 15:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and with a strong hand and outstretched arm (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 6:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
